        // The sequence must be 0, 1, 2, ..., k-1.
        // This means a[i] must be at least i for i < k.
        // And a[k-1] must be at least k-1.
        // The decreasing part must be k-1, k-2, ..., 0.
        // This means a[i] must be at least (n-1-i) for i >= k.
        // So, for a[0] == 0, we need a[i] >= i for i from 0 to k-1,
        // and a[i] >= (n-1-i) for i from k to n-1.
        // The peak element is a[k-1].
        // The condition for a sharpened array is that there exists a k
        // such that a_i >= i-1 for i < k and a_i >= n-i for i >= k.
        // If a[0] is 0, then the first element of the sharpened array must be 0.
        // So, the increasing part must be 0, 1, ..., k-1.
        // This means a[i] must be at least i for i from 0 to k-1.
