        // a[i] >= (k-1) - (i - (k-1)) = 2k-2-i for k <= i < n (this is wrong)
        // The decreasing part should be a_k > a_{k+1} > ... > a_n.
        // If a_k is the peak, then a_k must be at least k-1.
        // a_{k+1} must be at least k-2.
        // ...
        // a_n must be at least 0.
        // So, a_i must be at least (k-1) - (i-k) = 2k-1-i for i >= k.
        // This is equivalent to a_i >= (n-1-i) for i from k to n-1, if the peak is k-1.
        // Let's re-evaluate.
        // If a[0] == 0, then the first element of the sharpened array must be 0.
        // The sequence must be 0, 1, ..., peak_val, ..., 0.
        // The peak_val must be at least 0.
        // The increasing part: b_0=0, b_1=1, ..., b_{k-1}=k-1.
        // So, a[i] must be >= i for 0 <= i < k.
        // The decreasing part: b_{k-1}=k-1, b_k=k-2, ..., b_{n-1}=k-1-(n-1-(k-1)) = 2k-n-1.
        // This means a[i] must be >= (k-1) - (i-(k-1)) = 2k-2-i for k-1 <= i < n.
        // The minimum value for b_{n-1} is 0. So 2k-n-1 >= 0 => k >= (n+1)/2.
        //
        // A simpler way:
        // If a[0] == 0, then the first element of the sharpened array must be 0.
        // The increasing part must be 0, 1, 2, ...
        // So, for each i, a[i] must be at least i.
        // Let's find the maximum `inc_len` such that `a[i] >= i` for `0 <= i < inc_len`.
        int inc_len = 0;
        while (inc_len < n && a[inc_len] >= inc_len) {
            inc_len++;
        }
        // Now, `inc_len` is the length of the longest prefix that can be `0, 1, 2, ...`.
        // The peak can be at any index `p` from `0` to `inc_len - 1`.
        // If the peak is at index `p`, then the value at `p` is `p`.
        // The decreasing part must be `p, p-1, p-2, ..., 0`.
        // So, for `i > p`, `a[i]` must be at least `p - (i-p) = 2p - i`.
        // This means `a[i]` must be at least `(n-1-i)` if we want the last element to be 0.
        //
        // Let's check the condition for the whole array:
        // For a sharpened array, we need a peak `k` (0-indexed).
        // `b_0 < b_1 < ... < b_k` and `b_k > b_{k+1} > ... > b_{n-1}`.
        // The minimum values for `b_i` are `i` for `i <= k` and `k - (i-k)` for `i > k`.
        // So, we need `a[i] >= i` for `0 <= i <= k`.
        // And `a[i] >= k - (i-k)` for `k < i < n`.
        // The last element `b_{n-1}` must be `0`. So `k - (n-1-k) = 0` => `2k = n-1`.
        // This implies `k = (n-1)/2`.
        // This is only possible if `n` is odd.
        // If `n` is even, the last element cannot be 0 if the peak is `k` and `b_i = k-(i-k)`.
        //
        // The problem states "any strictly increasing or strictly decreasing array is sharpened".
        // This means `k` can be `0` (strictly decreasing) or `n-1` (strictly increasing).
        //
        // If `a[0] == 0`, then the first element of the sharpened array must be 0.
        // The increasing part must be `0, 1, 2, ...`.
        // The decreasing part must be `..., 2, 1, 0`.
        // So, we need `a[i] >= i` for the left side.
        // And `a[i] >= (n-1-i)` for the right side.
        //
        // Let's check if `a[i] >= i` for all `i` from `0` to `n-1`.
        // And `a[i] >= (n-1-i)` for all `i` from `0` to `n-1`.
        // This means `a[i] >= std::max(i, n-1-i)` for all `i`.
        // This is the condition for a "perfect" sharpened array with peak at `(n-1)/2` and value `(n-1)/2`.
        //
        // The condition is simpler:
        // We need to find a peak `k` (0-indexed).
        // For `0 <= i <= k`, we need `a[i] >= i`.
        // For `k < i < n`, we need `a[i] >= (k - (i-k))`.
        // The minimum value for `a[i]` is `0`.
        // So, for `k < i < n`, we need `a[i] >= std::max(0LL, k - (i-k))`.
        //
        // Let's define `L[i]` as the minimum value `a[i]` must take if it's part of the increasing sequence `0, 1, ..., i`.
        // `L[i] = i`.
        // Let's define `R[i]` as the minimum value `a[i]` must take if it's part of the decreasing sequence `..., i, i-1, ..., 0`.
        // `R[i] = n-1-i`.
        //
        // We need to find if there exists a `k` (0-indexed peak) such that:
        // `a[i] >= L[i]` for `0 <= i <= k`
        // `a[i] >= R[i]` for `k <= i < n`
        // Note that `a[k]` must satisfy both `a[k] >= L[k]` and `a[k] >= R[k]`.
        // So, `a[k] >= std::max(L[k], R[k])`.
        //
        // This is equivalent to:
        // Find the largest `k_left` such that `a[i] >= i` for all `0 <= i <= k_left`.
        // Find the smallest `k_right` such that `a[i] >= (n-1-i)` for all `k_right <= i < n`.
        // If `k_left >= k_right`, then a sharpened array is possible.
        //
        // Example: n=4, a = [0, 1, 1, 0]
        // L = [0, 1, 2, 3]
        // R = [3, 2, 1, 0]
        //
        // k_left:
        // a[0]=0 >= L[0]=0 (true)
        // a[1]=1 >= L[1]=1 (true)
        // a[2]=1 >= L[2]=2 (false)
        // So k_left = 1. (meaning indices 0, 1 satisfy L)
        //
        // k_right:
        // a[3]=0 >= R[3]=0 (true)
        // a[2]=1 >= R[2]=1 (true)
        // a[1]=1 >= R[1]=2 (false)
        // So k_right = 2. (meaning indices 2, 3 satisfy R)
        //
        // Is k_left >= k_right? 1 >= 2 (false). So "No". This matches example.
        //
        // Example: n=6, a = [100, 11, 15, 9, 7, 8]
        // L = [0, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5]
        // R = [5, 4, 3, 2, 1, 0]
        //
        // k_left:
        // a[0]=100 >= L[0]=0 (true)
        // a[1]=11 >= L[1]=1 (true)
        // a[2]=15 >= L[2]=2 (true)
        // a[3]=9 >= L[3]=3 (true)
        // a[4]=7 >= L[4]=4 (true)
        // a[5]=8 >= L[5]=5 (true)
        // So k_left = 5. (all indices satisfy L)
        //
        // k_right:
        // a[5]=8 >= R[5]=0 (true)
        // a[4]=7 >= R[4]=1 (true)
        // a[3]=9 >= R[3]=2 (true)
        // a[2]=15 >= R[2]=3 (true)
        // a[1]=11 >= R[1]=4 (true)
        // a[0]=100 >= R[0]=5 (true)
        // So k_right = 0. (all indices satisfy R)
        //
        // Is k_left >= k_right? 5 >= 0 (true). So "Yes". This matches example.

        int max_inc_idx = -1; // Max index `i` such that `a[0...i]` can be `0, 1, ..., i`
        for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i) {
            if (a[i] >= i) {
                max_inc_idx = i;
            } else {
                break;
            }
        }

        int min_dec_idx = n; // Min index `i` such that `a[i...n-1]` can be `..., n-1-i, ..., 0`
        for (int i = n - 1; i >= 0; --i) {
            if (a[i] >= (n - 1 - i)) {
                min_dec_idx = i;
            } else {
                break;
            }
        }

        if (max_inc_idx >= min_dec_idx) {
            std::cout << "Yes\n";
        } else {
            std::cout << "No\n";
        }

    } else { // a[0] > 0
        // If a[0] > 0, we can always decrease it to 0.
        // So the logic is the same as if a[0] was 0.
        // The only difference is that if a[0] is already 0, we can't decrease it further.
        // But the condition `a[i] >= i` already handles this.
        // If a[0] > 0, we can make it 0. So `a[0]` effectively becomes `0`.
        // The condition `a[0] >= 0` is always true.
        // So the logic should be the same.

        int max_inc_idx = -1;
        for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i) {
            if (a[i] >= i) {
                max_inc_idx = i;
            } else {
